  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Nourishing Oregon&apos;s Foster Children</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Foster children</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In collaboration with the Department of Health and Human Services and University of Oregon, SPOON facilitated a training needs assessment, including a survey and focus group discussions with foster parents and interviews and a survey with key child welfare staff to understand the nutrition and feeding issues of children in their care and identify training needs. SPOON is currently analyzing the needs assessment data to inform the design of the training curriculum and implementation in Lane County by end of 2015 and plan for scale statewide.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project aims to improve nutrition-related outcomes for foster children by equipping the foster care community with the knowledge and skills to prevent, detect and address nutrition and feeding problems. This pilot project in Lane Country, Oregon, directly targets the foster care community including foster parents, child welfare professionals, and training service providers and will be scaled to reach foster communities across the state to benefit all of Oregon&#x2019;s foster children.</narrative>
  </description>
